Name: LEONIDAS Watch
Company description: LEONIDAS was founded in 1842, some 120 years later it merged with Heuer creating the largest manufacturer of stopwatches and chronographs in Switzerland, and establishing Heuer-Leonidas as one of the biggest and most influential watch brands in the world.  During the 80's the company came under increasing pressure to compete with the influx of cheaper quartz models from China. The brandâ€™s reluctance to compromise quality over price saw Heuer-Leonidas become Tag-Heuer with Leonidas falling by the wayside.  It was in 2015 that Leonidas first tiptoed back into the watch making arena with the 5024, their first stand alone model since falling victim to the quartz crisis some 50 years earlier. Rather unsurprisingly upon their return Leonidas vowed never to use a movement powered by a battery.  The unorthodox positioning of the logo on the 5024 in the bottom half of the dial was no accident - it was in fact referencing the brandâ€™s historic past when Heuer-Leonidas dominated the supply of timing devices to major sporting events. Due to the hand configuration on a stopwatch itâ€™s not possible to place the logo in the traditional space. Instead itâ€™s positioned above the nbr 30 marker (or 6 on a watch ). It's a nice touch to see it taking up the same position some 50 years later.  Leonidas donâ€™t mass-produce their timepieces; with a Leonidas watch exclusivity of wear is dictated by the availability of the range rather than the ticket price. â€˜We donâ€™t claim to be an exclusive brand on one hand whilst simultaneously manufacturing  3000 watches a day on the otherâ€™ says Matthews (the current owner and CEO of the brand).

Company description: Wizway's goal is to bring the best of mobile technology to the world of Transport for mTicket services. Users benefit from the customer experience of mobile contactless, far superior to other technologies: easy and fast. They open their ticketing systems on mobile phones without compromising on the security, reliability and performance of their existing solutions. Since its first implementation in 2018 in Strasbourg, other major transport networks have deployed this solution: Paris Ile-de-France, Lille and SNCF TER. The use of smartphones to purchase and validate contactless transport tickets continues to progress and is making an effective contribution to barrier gestures.
